      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I'll keep the goblin references to a minimum. To answer your question, the hydrogen ions (H+) play a crucial role in the sensation of burning during high-intensity exercise. When lactic acid accumulates in your muscles, it dissociates into lactate (lactate ion, La-) and hydrogen ions (H+). The increased concentration of hydrogen ions in the muscle tissue disrupts the normal pH balance, leading to a decrease in pH.\n\nThis decrease in pH triggers a cascade of physiological responses, including the activation of pain-sensing nerve endings. The pain you experience is often described as a burning sensation, which is thought to be mediated by the activation of nociceptors, specialized nerve endings that detect changes in pH and other chemical signals.\n\nIn essence, the accumulation of lactic acid and the subsequent increase in hydrogen ions create an acidic environment in your muscles, which sends a signal to your nervous system that something is amiss. This signal is perceived as pain, which is why you experience the burning sensation in your quads during high-intensity exercise.",
